            </svg>
            Star on GitHub
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Terminal snippet -->
      <div class="mt-12 max-w-2xl">
        <CodeBlock title="terminal" code={heroCode} />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Decorative gradient -->
    <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 -z-10 w-1/2 h-full bg-gradient-to-l from-accent/5 to-transparent"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem Section -->
  <section class="bg-surface-alt border-y border-border">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-20 md:py-28">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-8">
          Databases weren't built for the cloud
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Traditional databases carry complexity from a pre-cloud era. Local disks, manual replication,
            consensus protocols, failover playbooks — each database you adopt brings a new operational model,
            new failure modes, and a new scaling story.
          </p>
          <p>
            Object storage changes the game. Services like S3 provide durable, highly-available, effectively
            infinite storage out of the box. But building correctly on object storage requires deep care —
            you need to handle write batching, caching, compaction, and snapshot isolation to get the
            performance developers expect.
          </p>
          <p>
            That work is substantially similar across databases. The write-ahead log, the compaction engine,
            the caching layer — it's the same problem solved slightly differently each time. What if you
            solved it once, and built every database on that shared foundation?
          </p>
          <p class="text-text font-medium">
            That's OpenData. Multiple focused databases, one operational model, zero infrastructure to manage.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Interactive Demo Section -->
